@Bill Bither I have been involved with one of the largest no-code/low-code implementations before they were a thing. I literally grew up in Tibco's backyard and have seen one of the largest (low-code implementations) and potential disasters with low-code. 

While the premise of low-code is strong and yes it will cut down the development time to some degree, it will not help with the design, architecture, or requirement gathering. In fact, the business logic is still the same regardless of whether you code your integration logic in one of the programming languages or in a low code program. Also, programmers (including me) very rarely appreciate the inefficiencies introduced by the visual interfaces of the no-code platforms as we can write code/debug way faster in Python, Java, .Net, etc. You might want to review the interview with Ted Needleman who writes for Accounting Today and reviews ERP systems for a living. He was involved with the development of one of the first ERP systems and have had the pleasure of getting invited by Bill Gates to review Microsoft's offerings. https://www.elevatiq.com/episode/user-friendly-erp-system/ He talks about this point.

The talented individual that you seem to be referring to in your note is similar to my skillset who has a background with Sarbanes Oxley and maintaining master data governance (deep knowledge of accounting, inventory, sales and operations planning, and regulatory compliance as well as multiple system expertise including programming) across systems. It's a nightmare to design flows across the systems when you have master data captured at multiple places. The more systems you introduce in the architecture without pre-baked integration, the more exception scenarios and failure points you are going to have in the architecture.

@Jon Forbord this is definitely an interesting question. Think of BPM as more of the business process documentation captured in a piece of software, where you can drill into the business perspective, process perspective, and then tech perspective. 

While the concept is powerful, it has never been mainstream. And it is typically used by companies that are very heavy in software development, custom dev, etc. For example, media, telco, tech, logistics, etc. Also, it is more prevalent in the CRM play as opposed to the ERP play. One of the largest vendors in the BPM space is Pegasystems, which is very heavy in the CRM play. There are other vendors such as Tibco ActiveMetrix, WebMethods, etc but again, they are primarily used in banking, telco, media, tech, etc.

While there are other vendors who claim to improve visibility into the large ERP implementations, at least I have not seen it majorly used any of the corporations unless an exec is super sold on this and wanted to implement it as they had too much money or time to do something. There is also a very thin line between iPaaS and BPM and some companies use them interchangeably. Even in this list, some of the tools captured might be more of the iPaaS than a true BPM.

It's not so much a migration, more of a re-implementation.
@youri.regnaud has taken the best approach that I've seen across many companies by focussing on interoperability and Event-driven integration.
Throw out the idocs and move to the rest API, but more than that, move the business towards 'event-driven' integration
